Baroka FC host Cape Town City FC in a Telkom Knockout quarter-final encounter at the New Peter Mokaba Stadium on Saturday.Bakgaga head into the cup encounter on the back of a four-game unbeaten streak, with their most recent result being a 0-0 draw against Kaizer Chiefs in the Absa Premiership.&nbsp;Kgoloko Thobejane's charges booked their spot in the quarters with a comprehensive 3-1 victory over Platinum Stars, which also marked the newly-promoted outfit's first home win of the season.&nbsp;The Limpopo-based outit occupy 10th place in the league standings, but Thobejane is confident that they will survive the drop this season."We are in the PSL and we are a team and we will stay," he told reporters."It is just that sometimes people will take us [lightly] somehow. We believe we can and we will [stay in the PSL] and there is no doubt."And people sometimes, because of Kgoloko maybe [are doubting us], so I'm assuring you that Baroka will stay and I'm sure it will be for the next 100 years," he said.Eric Tinkler's side booked their place in the quarter-finals with a hard-fought 2-0 victory against Blomefontein Celtic. Ironically, Cape Town City's last loss came at he hands of Baroka, who defeated them 2-1 at the Cape Town Stadium in October.The Cape outfit also defeated reigning Premiership champions Mamelodi Sundowns 2-1 in a league tie, before completing the double against Celtic - with a 1-0 victory in their most recent encounter.Lehlohonolo Majoro's solitary strike handed his side the victory and the former Orlando Pirates marksman drew praise from Tinkler for netting his first goal for the club."Shame, I think he deserves it. It's not for a lack of trying," he said in his post-match interview."He's worked extremely hard, you know. But there's that intelligence what he has, what you saw today."Baroka boast a full compliment of players, while Cape Town City will be without the services of influential midfielder Mpho Matsi, who picked up his fourth yellow card of the season in the victory against Celtic.